Backend + Web UI (Most Practical): 
Spring Boot = engine (makes Java web-ready)
GitHub = storage + commits
Render = hosting (makes it public)

👉 This is the real-world equivalent

🧠 Backend:
Spring Boot
Runs Java in background
With Spring Boot
Java runs as a server
You open:
http://localhost:8080
👉 And see output in browser ✅

🧠 UI:
HTML/CSS/JS (same as frontend)

🌍 Free hosting:
Render
Free tier
Handles Spring Boot nicely
Easier logs/debugging
Better for web UI apps

Steps: 
Install Git, VS Code

Go to: Spring Initializer
Fill options:
Project: Maven
Language: Java
Spring Boot: (latest default)
Group: com.example
Artifact: demo
Add dependency: 
Click:
👉 Add Dependencies → Spring Web
(VERY IMPORTANT — this enables browser UI)
Click Generate
👉 It downloads a .zip
Extract the zip: 
You’ll get a folder like:
demo/
 ├── src/
 ├── pom.xml
 
Open in VS Code:
File → Open Folder → select demo
🟩 What just happened?
👉 Spring Boot is already included via:
pom.xml
You don’t manually install anything.

🟨 Run the project (important):
In VS Code terminal:
./mvnw spring-boot:run
👉 Then open browser:
http://localhost:8080

🟥 Alternative (VS Code extension):
You can install:
Spring Boot Extension Pack
👉 It lets you generate projects inside VS Code
But honestly:
# 👉 Spring Initializr is simplest of all


Create GitHub repo: Go to GitHub. Click New Repository. Name it (same as your folder)
Upload Java project to GitHub: GitHub will show commands. Use each one at a time:
git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/your-repo.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

Every time you change something:
git add .
git commit -m "describe what you changed. type the exact(particular thing that u changed)"
git push

Connect GitHub to Render
Sign up
Click New → Web Service
Connect your GitHub repo

Configure
Render usually auto-detects Java, or you set:
Build command:
./mvnw install
Start command:
java -jar target/app.jar

Deploy
Get link

